The Edo State Governor, Godwin Obaseki has expressed sadness over the death of a popular highlife musician, Ambassador Osayomore Joseph who died on Saturday. The governor, in a statement he personally signed, described the music maestro as an enigmatic and versatile musician who according to him, had spread didactic messages via his “soulful and sonorous voice”. Obaseki recalled how the music legend exported the culture of Edo people to the world through his songs. He said the musician’s contribution to the creative industry in the state is as remarkable as it is transformational, stressing that Osayomore was a crucial voice in the quest to make society better. “His long music career, which started in the 1970s, was very productive and enriched the lives of many. The boldness and candour enmeshed in his rhythmic melodies earned him local and international acclaim. “I commiserate with the Osayomore family, fans and friends of the illustrious musician and pray that God will grant all the fortitude to bear this irreparable loss”, the statement added.